datastructures.queues

Class LinearPriorityQueue<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • datastructures.queues.LinearPriorityQueue<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    PriorityQueue<T>, Queue<T>, java.lang.Iterable<T>

    public class LinearPriorityQueue<T>
extends java.lang.Object
implements PriorityQueue<T>
    LinearPriorityQueue is a priority queue implemented as an array of common FIFO queues, where the queues themselves hold objects with the same priority in the order they arrived. It is important to understand that, because in a priority queue new elements can be added in pretty much any position of the data structure, a List is not a suitable container for the FIFO queues mentioned above, since it would only allow for adding an element at the first or last queue in the sequence. Thus, the statement in p.661 of Java Foundations, that a list of queues is a suitable implementation for a priority queue, is not completely correct. In this implementation, we will use a Java ArrayList, which allows us to add elements at any position in the structure. A more straightforward implementation of a priority queue as a special- case heap can be found in HeapPriorityQueue.java.
    Since:
    October 2013
    Author:
    Jason Filippou (jasonfil@cs.umd.edu)
    See Also:
    HeapPriorityQueue

      • LinearPriorityQueue

        public LinearPriorityQueue(Queue<T> other)
        The current implementation does not allow for copy-construction. The reason is that the iterator returns the objects contained themselves, not their priorities. It is therefore hard to produce the exact same queue as the one provided (simply considering a unique priority per object scanned would produce a semantically equivalent representation, but in terms of the memory model the two queues would be very different).
        Parameters:
        other - The queue to base the creation of the current object on.
        Throws:
        java.lang.UnsupportedOperationException - always
